Anglophone philosophers, such as Stanley Cavell, Hannah Arendt, Martin Heidegger, and John Rawls; Shuster reveals how various contemporary television series engage deeply with aesthetic and philosophical issues in modernism and modernity. What unifies the aesthetic and philosophical ambitions of new television is a commitment to portraying and exploring the family as the last site of political possibility in a world otherwise bereft of any other sources of traditional authority; consequently, at the heart of new television are profound political stakes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFamilies on television. 0aTelevision serieszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevision series--United States--History and criticism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aHannah Arendt.  aMartin Heidegger.  aStanley Cavell.  aaesthetics.  anew television.  aphenomenology.  aphilosophy of art.  apolitical philosophy.  atelevision series.  atelevision.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022650381340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226504001423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226504001/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles